    excerpt: "Most dropshipping guides are written by people who have never shipped an order. We run a live Shopify dropshipping store \u2014 here is what actually matters in 2026.",
    content: "Most dropshipping content online is written by people selling courses, not running stores. We operate a live Shopify dropshipping store in the fragrance and beauty niche, and this guide covers what we actually learned \u2014 including the mistakes.\n\n## What dropshipping looks like in 2026\n\nDropshipping is not dead, but the 2019 playbook is. Generic AliExpress products with 3-week shipping no longer convert. What works now is **supplier-backed catalog dropshipping**: partnering with a real distributor (in our case, a US fragrance wholesaler with 9,000+ SKUs) and running a properly merchandised store on top of their inventory.\n\n## Step 1 \u2014 Pick a supplier before a niche\n\nEveryone says pick a niche first. In practice, your supplier determines your margins, shipping speed, and return policy \u2014 which determine whether the business works at all. Evaluate suppliers on: US-based fulfillment, live inventory feeds (API or CSV), MAP pricing policies, and dropship fees. A supplier with a 19,000-row catalog and daily stock updates beats a trending product with no supply chain.\n\n## Step 2 \u2014 Import the catalog properly\n\nThis is where most stores fail silently. Bulk-importing thousands of products creates duplicate handles, draft products customers never see, and out-of-stock listings that burn ad spend. Our rules after doing this at scale:\n\n- Import through Matrixify, not the native Shopify importer, for anything over 1,000 SKUs\n- Always set the Published and Status columns explicitly \u2014 silent drafts are lost revenue\n- Sync inventory by SKU, and re-run availability checks weekly against the supplier\n- Rewrite supplier descriptions \u2014 duplicate manufacturer copy will not rank on Google\n\n## Step 3 \u2014 Margins that survive\n\nFragrance dropshipping margins run 15\u201335% after supplier fees. That means paid ads on cold traffic rarely work at the product level. What works: SEO on brand + product searches (\"versace eros 3.4 oz\"), email flows on abandoned carts, and collection pages built for buyers comparing prices.\n\n## Step 4 \u2014 The operations nobody talks about\n\nReturns, chargebacks, and supplier stockouts will consume more time than marketing. Set inventory policy to deny when out of stock, automate stock syncs, and keep 10\u201315% margin reserve for returns. \n\n## The honest verdict\n\nDropshipping in 2026 is a real business model with thin margins that rewards operators, not gamblers. If you treat it like a catalog-management and SEO business, it works. If you treat it like a lottery ticket, it does not.\n\n---\n\n**Ready to launch or upgrade your store?** eCeez handles full Shopify builds, migrations, and speed work. [See our store setup service](/shopify-store-setup-service).",
